-- allium: 3
-- turbo_kv_outliers.allium

-- Scope: outlier-aware quantisation — store the K highest-
-- magnitude coordinates of each rotated vector verbatim as
-- fp16 alongside their channel indices, and OVERWRITE the
-- codebook reconstruction at those channels on dequantise.
-- Addresses the heavy-tail problem in attention activations
-- that a single global codebook fits poorly. Composes on top
-- of core TurboQuant.
--
-- Citable sources:
--
--   [PAPER]       Zandieh et al., arxiv 2504.19874. Paper's §4
--                 "application to attention" discusses per-
--                 channel bit allocation as the paper-prescribed
--                 handling of heavy-tail attention activations.
--                 [QUANT.CPP]'s outlier variant is described
--                 there as "a simpler local form" of this idea.
--
--   [QUANT.CPP]   Ships the outlier handling as two concrete
--                 variants in include/turboquant/tq_types.h:
--
--                 block_tq_turbo_kv_4bo (Variant G) layout:
--                   norm(2) + residual_norm(2) + inv_std(2)
--                   + _pad(2) + mse_4bit(64)
--                   + out_indices[8] + out_values_fp16[16]
--                   = 96 bytes per 128-element block
--
--                 block_tq_turbo_kv_3bo (same idea, 3-bit base):
--                   norm(2) + residual_norm(2) + inv_std(2)
--                   + _pad(2) + mse_3bit(48)
--                   + out_indices[8] + out_values_fp16[16]
--                   = 80 bytes per 128-element block
--
--                 The per-block outlier count is fixed at
--                 #define TQ_KV_4BO_OUTLIERS 8
--                 tq_types.h comment:
--                     "the K=8 largest |rotated[i]| values are
--                      stored verbatim as FP16 with their
--                      channel index, and OVERWRITE the codebook
--                      reconstruction at dequantize time."
--                 Comparing block sizes against non-outlier
--                 variants at same head_dim:
--                     4b   = 72 B    4bo  = 96 B   (+24 B)
--                     3b   = 56 B    3bo  = 80 B   (+24 B)
--                     5b   = 88 B
--
--   [TONBI-V3]    Does not ship block-local outlier handling.
--                 V3 mentions "outlier-aware channel allocation"
--                 as part of community V3 framing but its
--                 compressors_v3.py implementation uses MSE-only
--                 without per-block outliers.
--
-- Goal: specify the outlier-augmented wire format and the
-- overwrite-at-dequantise semantics. This is a wire format
-- extension to the core QuantizedHead entity, adding an
-- optional outlier list.
--
-- Includes: outlier selection (top-K by |rotated[i]|), outlier
-- storage (index + fp16 value), dequantise overwrite.
-- Excludes: base codebook (core spec), residual window, layer-
-- adaptive, asymmetric bits. Composes with all of those.

-- ============================================================
-- External entities
-- ============================================================

external entity Tensor {
    data: Set<Decimal>
    count: Integer
}

-- ============================================================
-- Value types
-- ============================================================

-- Per-block outlier record: channel index + fp16 verbatim value.
entity OutlierEntry {
    channel_index: Integer
    value: Decimal          -- fp16-encoded verbatim rotated value
}

-- Extended quantised head carrying both the codebook indices
-- and an outlier list. Base QuantizedHead remains the same;
-- this entity adds the outlier slot.
entity QuantizedHeadWithOutliers {
    norm: Decimal
    inv_std: Decimal
    indices: Set<Integer>   -- base codebook indices (head_dim entries)
    outliers: Set<OutlierEntry>  -- K largest-magnitude channels
}

-- ============================================================
-- Config
-- ============================================================

config {
    -- Number of outlier channels per block. [QUANT.CPP] uses a
    -- compile-time constant of 8 (TQ_KV_4BO_OUTLIERS). 8 is
    -- large enough to capture typical heavy-tail behaviour in
    -- transformer KV without ballooning per-block overhead:
    -- 8 channels × (1 byte index + 2 bytes fp16) = 24 bytes
    -- per 128-element block, i.e. +1.5 bytes per element.
    outlier_count: Integer = 8

    -- Fraction of a block's total magnitude captured by the
    -- outliers, used for diagnostic invariants. Empirical
    -- guidance: 8 outliers typically capture >40% of total
    -- rotated-vector magnitude on attention activations at
    -- head_dim ≥ 128.
    min_outlier_magnitude_fraction: Decimal = 0.1
}

-- ============================================================
-- Open questions
-- ============================================================

open question "Outlier count tuning: [QUANT.CPP] uses 8 per 128-element block. Optimal value likely scales with head_dim and depends on the activation distribution's tail heaviness. At head_dim=256 the proportional choice would be 16, not 8 — but measurements at 9B have not been done."

open question "Outlier selection metric: [QUANT.CPP] selects the K largest by |rotated[i]|. Alternatives: K largest by reconstruction error vs the codebook, K largest by contribution to attention score estimation. The magnitude heuristic is computationally cheapest; attention-aware selection could improve quality at the cost of a pre-pass through the selected queries."

open question "Paper's per-channel bit allocation vs quant.cpp's local outliers: [PAPER] §4 describes a global per-channel bit budget (channels with heavier tails get more bits). [QUANT.CPP]'s 4bo/3bo approximates this locally with a fixed-count outlier list per block. The paper-global approach has better distortion-rate in theory; the local approach has simpler wire format and streaming compatibility. Spec models the local variant; a global-budget sibling spec could be added if measurement justifies it."

open question "Composition with asymmetric K/V: a deployer could enable outliers on K only (preserving attention-score quality where heavy tails matter most) and skip outliers on V (which the softmax already smooths out). Not currently modelled — this spec applies outliers uniformly to whichever tensor it attaches to."

-- ============================================================
-- Composite rules
-- ============================================================

-- Quantise with outlier extraction:
--   1. Compute L2 norm, normalize, rotate (same as core).
--   2. Identify the outlier_count channels with largest |rotated[i]|.
--   3. Store those channels' values verbatim as fp16 with
--      their channel indices.
--   4. Run the base codebook argmin over ALL channels (including
--      the outliers) — the codebook indices for outlier channels
--      will be overwritten at dequantise time, so their codebook
--      approximation is never used. Quant.cpp pragmatically
--      leaves them in the index stream for layout simplicity.
rule QuantizeHeadWithOutliers {
    when: QuantizeHeadWithOutliers(tensor, seed)

    requires: tensor.count > 0
    requires: L2_norm(tensor.data) > 0.0

    let norm = L2_norm(tensor.data)
    let normalized = normalize(tensor.data, norm)
    let rotated = RHT_forward(normalized, tensor.count, config.seed)
    let max_val = max_abs(rotated)
    let inv_std = config.cent_max / max_val
    let indices = nearest_centroid(rotated, inv_std, turbo_kv_4b_codebook)
    let outliers = select_top_k_by_magnitude(rotated, config.outlier_count)

    ensures: QuantizedHeadWithOutliers.created(
        norm: norm,
        inv_std: inv_std,
        indices: indices,
        outliers: outliers
    )
}

-- Dequantise with outlier overwrite:
--   1. Reconstruct the base codebook values for ALL channels.
--   2. Overwrite the outlier_count outlier channels with their
--      stored fp16 values (pre-rotation, unit-sphere coords).
--   3. Apply inverse RHT.
--   4. Rescale by norm.
rule DequantizeHeadWithOutliers {
    when: DequantizeHeadWithOutliers(block)

    requires: block.inv_std > 0.0
    requires: block.indices.count > 0

    let codebook_values = reconstruct_codebook(block, turbo_kv_4b_codebook)
    let with_outliers = overwrite_at_channels(codebook_values, block.outliers)
    let dequant_rotated = RHT_inverse(with_outliers, block.indices.count, config.seed)
    let reconstructed = rescale(dequant_rotated, block.norm)

    ensures: Tensor.created(
        data: reconstructed,
        count: block.indices.count
    )
}

-- ============================================================
-- Invariants
-- ============================================================

-- Outlier channels must be valid indices into the head vector.
invariant OutlierIndicesInBounds {
    for block in QuantizedHeadsWithOutliers:
        for outlier in block.outliers:
            outlier.channel_index >= 0 and
            outlier.channel_index < block.indices.count
}

-- Outlier list size matches config.
invariant OutlierCountConsistent {
    for block in QuantizedHeadsWithOutliers:
        block.outliers.count = config.outlier_count
}

-- No duplicate outlier channels — each channel appears at most
-- once in the outlier list.
invariant OutliersUnique {
    for block in QuantizedHeadsWithOutliers:
        for o1 in block.outliers:
            for o2 in block.outliers:
                o1 = o2 or o1.channel_index != o2.channel_index
}

-- ============================================================
-- Implementation notes
-- ============================================================

-- [QUANT.CPP] reference: block_tq_turbo_kv_4bo in
-- include/turboquant/tq_types.h, struct layout quoted at the
-- top of this file. The 96-byte layout encodes:
--   8 bytes header (norm + residual_norm + inv_std + pad)
--   64 bytes mse_indices (128 × 4-bit packed)
--   8 bytes out_indices (8 × uint8 channel indices)
--   16 bytes out_values (8 × fp16 verbatim)
--
-- Selection implementation in [QUANT.CPP]
-- (src/core/tq_turbo_kv.c, quantize path): scan the rotated
-- array, maintain a min-heap of top-K by absolute value. For
-- K=8 and n=128 the heap-vs-sort tradeoff is marginal;
-- [QUANT.CPP] uses an in-place partial sort.
--
-- Our llama.cpp port does NOT implement outlier handling. The
-- only turbo_kv_* type registered is TURBO_KV_4B (no-outliers
-- variant). Adopting 4bo/3bo requires:
--   - New ggml type TURBO_KV_4BO (96 bytes per 128 elements)
--   - New quantise / dequantise / vec_dot implementations that
--     handle the outlier overwrite at the right pipeline stage
--   - Vulkan / CUDA / ROCm shader variants for the same
--
-- Approximate implementation cost: high. Each kernel (quantise,
-- dequantise, get_rows, set_rows, FA) needs an outlier-aware
-- variant. This is a sibling-spec at about the same effort
-- level as adding a whole new precision tier.
--
-- Quality evidence: [QUANT.CPP] has not published a direct
-- 4b-vs-4bo PPL comparison. Paper §4's theoretical argument is
-- that outlier handling reduces distortion-rate at fixed
-- average bit budget, matching empirical findings in related
-- LLM-quantisation literature (SmoothQuant, AWQ, GPTQ all
-- address activation outliers in various ways).
